The Vita FPGA Architecture Subproject is licensed under The VitaSet
License.

The Vita FPGA Architecture Verilog files VitaFPGAArchLogicBlock.v and
VitaFPGAArchMemoryBlock.v are bugfree.

Using two bit input, one bit output nand or two bit input, one bit
output nor gates, one can express any possible truth table.

The VitaFPGAArchMemoryBlock.v file implements a D-Flip Flop with two
configurable single bit inputs and two configurable single bit outputs
that output the same one bit value in two directions.

The VitaFPGAArchLogicBlock.v file implements a LUT2 with two
configurable one bit inputs and two one bit outputs outputting the same
one bit value in two directions.

A Vita FPGA Architecture Logic Block can act as an Vita FPGA
Architecture Interconnect Block, by programming the LUT2 to ignore
either the most significant bit input or the least significant bit
input, listening to only one of the single bit inputs to output the
same one bit value in two directions. Then, two Vita FPGA Architecture
Interconnect Blocks can read that one bit value and output the same one
bit value in four directions. As you can see, a single one bit input
and one or more Vita FPGA Architecture Interconnect Blocks can cause
more and more Vita FPGA Architecture Logic Blocks to receive the same
one bit input value. However, each singular Vita FPGA Architecture
Logic Block added can only add one more output direction for the same
one bit input value.

If however, your Vita FPGA Architecture Logic Blocks don't need to
receive any more of the same one bit input value caused by a single one
bit input, each Vita FPGA Architecture Logic Block can be programmed to
ignore none of the two single bit inputs, or both of the single bit
inputs.

The VitaFPGAArchMemoryBlock.v file's
IOReconfigurationQuadrupleDTypeFlipFlopRegister internal register
determines what two sides are the two configurable single bit inputs,
and what two directions will receive the same one bit value from the
two configurable single bit outputs.

The VitaFPGAArchLogicBlock.v file's
IOReconfigurationTripleDTypeFlipFlopRegister internal register
determines what two sides are the two configurable single bit inputs,
and what two directions will receive the same one bit value from the
two configurable single bit outputs.

Thus, any possible truth table can be expressed with enough Vita FPGA
Architecture Logic Blocks and with enough Vita FPGA Architecture Memory
Blocks. Thus, any integrated circuit could run on the Vita FPGA
Architecture, given enough Vita FPGA Architecture Logic Blocks and Vita
FPGA Architecture Memory Blocks are available.

You are welcome to check out how it works, as explained by the
Documentation file and the source code files.

The Vita FPGA Architecture Synthesizer Subproject is under development,
and is licensed under The VitaSet License.
